title: For Sale:  RUDENESS
postcontent: I'm venting. There's a lot of bad behavior on Armslist these days. Here are the top 5. 1.  If somebody sends you an email, reply. Many offers are legit. It's rude to ask folks to send offers and then not bother with a reply. 2.  If you tell folks to text offers, reply. Even if you don't like their offer, reply. A simple " no thank you" works. 3.  Stop with the silly FREE or $1 listings. You have no intention of giving your guns away and you're sure as hell not selling them for $1. And no, nobody is looking at your listing thinking you're selling a $500 gun for $1. 4.  Don't tell someone you're committed to trading or selling and then stop replying to emails or texts when you've changed your mind.  That's unprofessional. If your status has changed, just communicate. 5.  While this is very subjective, stop with over-valuing your guns and under-valuing the other person's guns.  It makes for a lousy exchange. Sincerely. Peter Hill

title: For Sale:  Custom Hand-made O1 fixed blade
postcontent: I'm selling this custom designed, hand-made fixed blade, in O1 tool steel. O1 is a carbon steel and will need to be cleaned and oiled to prevent rust. It lives in a humidity controlled safe and has been dry oiled.The knife is a full tang blade, built with black G10 scales (matte finish) with white G10 liners. Scales and liners are epoxied and then bolted to the blade tang using stainless steel corby bolts. The blade has a high saber grind with a machine finish (scotchbrite belt) on the primary grind and a hand rubbed satin finish on the flats. The handle portion of the blade is drilled out to create better balance and lighten the knife. Heat treated to Rockwell hardness 58-60. I have other knives by the same maker and his craftsmanship and fit and finish is fantastic.Knife basics:Overall length- 7.5" (I have medium sized hands and its a perfect fit for me)Blade length- 3.5"Cutting Edge length- 3.4"Blade thickness (at ricasso)- 0.125"This knife comes with a handmade thermoformed Holstex sheath with a carbon fiber texture. The sheath has 1/4" eyelets spaced at intervals that will allow for multiple carry options. It has an attached but removable webbing belt loop that can be switched around to allow the user to wear the knife on their left side. Sheath has drain holes molded in to allow water and dirt to escape. All screws loctited. The sheath provides very good retention. On other sheaths from the same maker, I put overhook clips on each side and carry it OWB but inside the belt. Works great that way and conceals perfectly.I designed it, and had a very talented knife maker build it. Its a great knife, perfect size for EDC and is very sharp. It has never been used or resharpened.I paid $150 for it and its worth every penny of that, and more in my opinion.
